@NODE Description
@TITLE "BackDrop: Description"
@TOC "Main"
@PREV "Main"
@NEXT "Installation"

          DESCRIPTION OF BACKDROP

BackDrop  automatically changes the Workbench Window Picture at an interval set
by  the  user.   It continually performs this function as a background process,
requiring no further attention.

Backdrop randomly selects images from a user-specified drawer.  This drawer may
contain  any  number  and  type  of image files either readable by the system's
datatypes or capable of being displayed by the WBPattern Preference program.

Backdrop  is  for computers with the AmigaDOS 3.1 through 3.9 operating systems
only.    This  version is AmigaDOS 3.9 compatible.  For AmigaDOS 3.1, use prior
version 1.4 and for AmigaDOS 3.5, use prior version 1.5.

For  best  results,  users  should save their WBPattern preferences to have the
Workbench  Pictures "Layout" set to "Tile" mode.  Subsequently, BackDrop should
be  supplied  either  small  image  patterns  or  large  images which match the
Workbench  Window  dimensions.    (Although  BackDrop  can   handle full-screen
photographed,  painted, or modeled images, results will not be as pleasing when
the  width  and  length of these large images are not the same as the Workbench
width and length.)

Sales slogan: Don't like the way your Workbench looks? 

              Wait a few seconds - with BackDrop.

     @{"Installing BackDrop" link Installation}

Related topics:

     @{"What is meant by the term Workbench Window Picture?                  " link WWP}
     @{"Why BackDrop's function cannot be done using an AmigaDOS/ARexx script" link Why}
     @{"What mechanism does BackDrop use to display images?                  " link How}
     @{"Why doesn't BackDrop work under AmigaDOS 2.x or 1.x?                 " link Why2}
     @{"Why doesn't BackDrop 1.5 or earlier work under AmigaDOS 3.9?         " link Why3}
     (Note:  If  you are running older 3.x AmigaDOS versions, older versions of
      BackDrop will work.  See @{"Revision History" link About})

@ENDNODE

@NODE WWP
@TITLE "BackDrop: What is the Workbench Window Picture?"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Description

     WHAT IS MEANT BY THE TERM WORKBENCH WINDOW PICTURE?

The  term  "Workbench  Window  Picture" refers to a feature of the AmigaDOS 3.x
"WBPattern" preference program located in the "Sys:Prefs/" drawer.  "WBPattern"
allows  the  user  to  place an image file within the window of Workbench.  All
Workbench icons and icon text are overlaid on the image.

If  Workbench is in backdrop mode, the "picture" will fill the entire Workbench
screen.    Otherwise,  the  "picture"  will  only  occupy  the  boarders of the
Workbench window.

The  normal  procedure for setting the "Workbench Window Picture" is to run the
"Sys:Prefs/WBPattern"  program;  select  "Workbench" on the "Placement" gadget;
select  "Picture"  on  the "Type" gadget; specify an image by using the "Select
Picture..." button; and finally selecting the "Use" button.

BackDrop  has  the  effect  of  performing   this   function   periodically and
automatically  in  the  background, selecting images that the user has prepared
and consigned to a single drawer.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Why
@TITLE "Backdrop: Why BackDrop?"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Description

     WHY BACKDROP'S FUNCTION CANNOT BE DONE USING AN AMIGADOS
                         OR AREXX SCRIPT

Basically,  it  is  because  the  WBPattern  program does not accept an "image"
argument.    The  only  way  to  feed WBPattern an image is to have a WBPattern
preset  file made up.  To perform BackDrop's function for a pool of images, one
would  have  to make up a preset file for each individual image.  This approach
is far too tedious to be practical.

@ENDNODE

@NODE How
@TITLE "BackDrop: What mechanism does BackDrop use to display the random images?"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Description

     WHAT MECHANISM DOES BACKDROP USE TO DISPLAY THE RANDOM IMAGES?

BackDrop  makes use of the "Use" argument of the WBPattern program.  The preset
file that BackDrop uses is always the same: "Env:BackDrop.prefs".  This file is
surgically  altered  by BackDrop during each cycle to contain the path and name
of the image file that has been randomly selected.

The  skeleton  for  each  WBPattern file that BackDrop displays is based on the
archival  file  "Sys:Prefs/Env-Archive/sys/WBPattern.prefs",  the file saved by
the  "Save"  button  in the WBPattern preferences program.  Therefore, whatever
quality  settings,  layout  mode,  screen pattern or picture or window image or
pattern  is  set  by  the WBPAttern preferences program will be carried through
with  BackDrop's  displays.   In other words, the user does not lose any of the
screen, window and quality settings when BackDrop operates.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Why2
@TITLE "BackDrop: Why doesn't BackDrop work under AmigaDOS 2.x or 1.x?"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Description

     WHY DOESN'T BACKDROP WORK UNDER AMIGADOS 2.X OR 1.X?

Since  the  WBPattern  program under AmigaDOS 2.x does not have the facility to
paint  a  picture  on  the  Workbench  window,  BackDrop will not operate under
AmigaDOS 2.x (although running BackDrop under AmigaDOS 2.x is not fatal).

Since  AmigaDOS  1.x  does  not  contain a WBPattern program, BackDrop will not
operate under those operating systems.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Why3
@TITLE "BackDrop: Why Doesn't BackDrop 1.5 or earlier work under Amigados 3.9?"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Description

     WHY DOESN'T BACKDROP 1.5 OR EARLIER WORK UNDER AMIGADOS 3.9?

The  AmigaDOS  WBPattern  program and prefs file format has changed between 3.1
and  3.5,  and again between 3.5 and 3.9.  Older versions of BackDrop will work
under these older versions

@ENDNODE

@NODE Installation
@TITLE "BackDrop: Installation"
@TOC Main
@PREV Description
@NEXT Configuration

     INSTALLING BACKDROP

The  first  three  items  below  are already present in a standard AmigaDOS 3.x
system  configuration,  and  are  listed as a formality since BackDrop requires
them. BackDrop will fail if they are not present.

1. Ensure  the AmigaDOS 3.9 "WBPattern" preference program is present in the
   "Sys:Prefs" drawer of your system.

2. Ensure the file "WBPattern.prefs" is present in the
   "Sys:Prefs/Env-Archive/sys" drawer.

3. Ensure the AmigaDOS 3.9 "Screenmode" preference program is present in the
   "Sys:Prefs" drawer of your system.

4. Setting up an Image Directory:

   a) Make or find a drawer that contains image files readable by the WBPattern
      preference  program.    These  include  by  default those types of images
      supported by the datatypes installed on your system.  This drawer will be
      referred to herein as the "Image Directory".  It may contain a mixture of
      readable  image  file  types (i.e., IFF, GIF, JPG, BMP, etc...) and their
      respective icon files, if available.  Any subdirectories within the Image
      Directory will be ignored by BackDrop.

   b) Do not allow any non-image files (other than icons files) in the "Image
      Directory", or else the computer may crash.

   c) The Image Directory should contain images which can either be "tiled",
      "scaled" or "centered" on the WorkBench Window.  These modes are known as
      "layouts" in AmigaDOS 3.9.  BackDrop will work with the layout mode which
      was  pre-saved  in  the  WBPattern program.    However, BackDrop does not
      currently  allow  for  layout  mode  changes on the fly.  It is therefore
      prefereable to group images in the Image Directory which can be all tiled
      or all centered or all scaled (or all scaled well).

   d) To  obtain  the  fastest  image  change  performance, use IFF images.
      These require no datatype translation and are immediately mapped onto the
      Workbench window.

      GIF files take longer to display, but also work satisfactorily.  Remember
      that  the  system  must convert these to IFF before being able to display
      them.

      JPG files take the longest to display and can slow down your computer CPU
      significantly  with  each translation.  It is suggested that you increase
      the "Interval" setting of BackDrop to accommodate this delay so that each
      image receive some appreciable display time.

5. Place BackDrop and BackDrop.guide together in any drawer you desire.

6. The  BackDrop icon ("BackDrop.info") MUST coexist with BackDrop, even if the
   user  intends to initiate BackDrop from a command line.
   
   IMPORTANT:  This icon must have alternate image highlighting, as is
   provided, for BackDrop to run.

          @{"Configuring BackDrop         " link Configuration}


@ENDNODE

@NODE Configuration
@TITLE "BackDrop: Configuration"
@TOC Main
@PREV Installation
@NEXT Startup

     CONFIGURING BACKDROP

There  is  no need to preconfigure BackDrop before running it.  All adjustments
may  be  made  during  program  execution.  Furthermore, BackDrop automatically
saves the configuration to the BackDrop icon while it is executing.

There are only two configurable BackDrop program icon tooltypes:

     Interval = <seconds>                       (default = 15)

     ImageDirectory = <path specification>      (default = BackDrop directory)


     Tooltype example:
     -------------------------------------------
     | Interval = 60                           |
     | ImageDirectory = Images:WBPatternPics/  |
     -------------------------------------------


     Tooltype punctuation rules:
     
     1.   Do not use quotation mark characters.
     2.   The Image Directory <path specification> must end in a ":" or a "/".

     Tooltype definitions:

     Interval       - How many seconds will BackDrop wait until it will change
                      the  Workbench  Window Picture.  This should be a numeric
                      value between 15 and 300.  Do not use quotation marks.

                      If  a  non-numeric  Interval  tooltype  is   present when
                      BackDrop is launched, it will assume it to be the default
                      of  15.    The default is also assumed for numeric values
                      less  than  15.   Numeric values greater than 300 will be
                      automatically reduced to 300.

     ImageDirectory - What path (directory) BackDrop will randomly select
                      image  files from.  When specifying this tooltype, do not
                      use  quotation marks.  The path specification must end in
                      a colon (":") or an upslash ("/").  Do not specify a file
                      name or location in this tooltype.
                      
                      If  the  user  supplies   a   nonexistent   or improperly
                      formatted  path,  BackDrop will interrupt image retrieval
                      process  during  "Go" mode.  Then the user is notified of
                      the  problem, and returned to the "Control Window", where
                      a new image directory specification can be set.

When  restarting BackDrop, the interval and image directory settings saved from
the previous session will automatically be read in and take effect.

The  user  may  wish to run the WBPattern program supplied with AmiagDOS 3.9 to
preset  and  save  the  quality,  layout, screen pattern or picture, and window
pattern  or  picture  to  accompany each BackDrop presentation.  Other than the
Workbench  Window  Picture,  all  other  parameters  are taken from the "saved"
WBPattern preference.

Refer  to  @{"Operation"  link Operation} for configuration changes that can be accomplished
during BackDrop execution.

     @{"Starting Up BackDrop" link Startup}

@ENDNODE

@NODE Startup
@TITLE "BackDrop: Startup"
@TOC Main
@PREV Configuration
@NEXT Operation

          STARTING UP BACKDROP

It is recommended that the Workbench Window be placed in "BackDrop" mode to get
the  best  visual  impact.   This is easily accomplished by selecting the first
item in the "Workbench" menu of the "Workbench" window labeled "BackDrop".

Additionally, the user may wish to start BackDrop before any programs that will
create  a  Workbench-resident  window.    In  this way, the user can, by way of
BackDrop,  readily  change  the  Workbench  screenmode  for best display of the
images.

Non-registered users must start the BackDrop program from the Workbench.

Workbench Startup:       Open or double-click on the BackDrop icon.  BackDrop
                         will  automatically  read   the   interval   and image
                         directory tooltypes of this icon, if any.
                         
                         The  "BackDrop  Control  Window"  will  appear  if the
                         program has found the necessary support files.
                         
                         At this time, registered users should enter the
                         @{"input sequence" link Input}.

Command Line Startup:    To startup in this manner, (registered) users must
                         supply the @{"pass-code" link Passcode}.

                         The  starting  environment of the command line must be
                         pointed to the drawer that Backdrop is located in.

                         The command line must be of the form:

                              BackDrop #?<Pass-code>#?

                              where "#?" represents any sequence of characters
                              or no characters

                         If  the  Pass-code  is  not  supplied,   BackDrop will
                         terminate.  Furthermore, the icon file "BackDrop.info"
                         must coexist with the BackDrop program file, even if
                         the program is lauched from a command line input.

                         Registered  users  who  start  BackDrop in this manner
                         will  be  preempted  from  having  to  enter the Input
                         Sequence in the Control Window.

                         This  version of BackDrop does not pass "Interval" and
                         "ImageDirectory"  command  line   arguments.  However,
                         BackDrop  will  read  and   obey   the   BackDrop icon
                         tooltypes  even  when  initiated from a command line. 
                         Furthermore, it will automatically save the "Interval"
                         and  "ImageDirectory"  settings  to  the BackDrop icon
                         during  execution,  even  if  it  was initiated from a
                         command  line.    Therefore,  users who startup from a
                         command  line  retain  the  capability  of   having an
                         auto-saving  and auto-loading BackDrop configuration. 

@ENDNODE

@NODE Operation
@TITLE "BackDrop: Operation"
@TOC Main
@PREV Configuration
